CLASSROOM OBSERVATION - VISIT 1

Teacher: Tredoux Willemse
Date: October 23, 2024
Time: 9:00 AM - 11:30 AM (Morning Work Cycle)
Location: Whale Class PreK 4, Beijing International School

---

PHYSICAL ENVIRONMENT - FIRST IMPRESSIONS

This is my first formal observation of the year, about a month into school. The room setup is basic but functional. 

Practical Life area: Most materials are out and accessible. Pouring station looks good - pitchers are child-sized, trays are organized. Sweeping materials in their spot. Buttoning/zipping frames on the shelf. Some trays need cleaning but overall solid start.

Sensorial area: Pink Tower, Brown Stair, Red Rods all present. Knobbed cylinders organized. Color tablets Box 1 and Box 2 available. Everything is at child height like it should be.

Math/Language: Limited materials out right now - that's intentional. At this stage of the year we're focusing on practical life and sensorial foundation. Will add more math and language materials as kids get ready.

Work mat basket: Full, organized, kids know where to get them.

Overall environment: 6/10. It's functional and organized but still feels new. Kids are still learning where things go. Some materials get mixed up. That's normal for October.

---

MORNING ROUTINE (9:00-9:15)

Kids arrive at different times. Most can hang up their backpacks and find their name card to sign in independently. Emma (5) and Oscar (4) do this perfectly. Leo (4.5) still needs reminders.

Mia (2.5) needs a lot of help with everything - that's expected for her age. Her mom stays for a few minutes, which helps.

Circle time: Short welcome, talked about what materials are available today, reviewed ground rules (walk, use quiet voices, respect others' work). Kept it under 10 minutes - young kids don't need long explanations.

---

WORK CYCLE OBSERVATIONS (9:15-11:15)

9:20 AM - Emma chose Pink Tower. This is maybe her 5th time with it. Built it slowly, carefully. Did the alignment check on her own. Concentration about 15 minutes. Good.

9:25 AM - Leo went straight for pouring work. He LOVES water activities. Made a small mess but cleaned it up himself without me saying anything. Progress. He's building self-correction skills.

9:30 AM - Oscar and Noah both wanted the same material (Red Rods). Had to intervene. Showed them how to check if material is in use - look at the shelf, if it's not there someone's using it. Redirected Noah to Brown Stair. Small conflict but handled okay.

9:40 AM - Sophia at art table. She defaults to art a lot. This is her third day in a row choosing painting. May need to gently guide her toward other areas. She's avoiding the structured materials. Note to address this.

9:50 AM - Chloe (4.5) working with Color Tablets Box 1. Matching red, blue, yellow. Quick and accurate. She's ready for Box 2 (more colors). Will present that next week.

10:00 AM - Mia attempting to fold cloths. This is hard for her - she's young and her fine motor is still developing. I sat with her for a few minutes, did it together. She needs more one-on-one time than older kids. That's fine.

10:15 AM - Lucas (5) sweeping. He swept the same spot for 10 minutes. Didn't actually sweep up anything (no crumbs there) but the PROCESS is what matters. He's practicing the movement, building coordination. Will introduce him to other practical life exercises soon - he's ready for more challenge.

10:30 AM - Zoe (5) chose Pink Tower after Emma returned it. She's newer to this material. Built it but had two cubes in wrong order. I waited to see if she'd notice. She didn't. After she finished I said "let's check it together" and we did the alignment check. She found her mistake and fixed it. Good learning moment.

10:45 AM - Several kids getting restless. Energy level rising. This is normal after 90 minutes of work time. Some kids ready for outdoor break, others still engaged.

---

CONCENTRATION PATTERNS

At this early stage of the year, most kids working 10-15 minutes per material. That's normal for October. A few kids (Emma, Chloe, Leo when he's interested) can go 20+ minutes.

Younger kids (Mia, Noah) shorter attention spans - 5-10 minutes. Expected.

Work cycle is developing but not yet fully established. Still lots of wandering, choosing work then abandoning it, checking what others are doing. This will improve over time as they build concentration skills.

---

MATERIALS BEING USED

Popular: Pouring activities, Pink Tower, sweeping
Medium use: Color tablets, folding cloth, Brown Stair
Not used today: Red Rods (conflict prevented access), knobbed cylinders

Practical life is the most used area by far. That's appropriate - this is the foundation. These activities build coordination, concentration, and order. 

Sensorial materials coming in second. Kids are ready for visual discrimination work.

---

TEACHER ROLE TODAY

Did 4 presentations:
1. Pink Tower to Zoe (first time)
2. Color Tablets Box 1 to Noah  
3. Folding cloth to Mia (review)
4. Pouring (beans) to new student

Otherwise mostly observation. Intervened a few times:
- Redirected Noah during Red Rods conflict
- Reminded three kids to walk (they were running)
- Helped Mia with coat zipper
- Asked Sophia to choose something besides painting

Trying to observe more, talk less. Let the materials teach. This is hard for me - I want to help constantly. Learning to step back.

---

INDEPENDENCE BUILDING

Most kids can:
- Get a mat
- Choose a material
- Carry it to their space
- Work with it (with varying levels of success)
- Return it (sometimes to wrong spot but they're trying)

Most kids cannot yet:
- Work for extended time without checking in
- Solve conflicts independently
- Self-correct all mistakes
- Clean up perfectly

That's all normal for month one. Independence is a process.

---

SOCIAL DYNAMICS

Generally peaceful classroom. A few conflicts (mostly over materials - two kids want the same thing). 

Emma and Chloe work near each other sometimes - not together but parallel. They like each other.

Leo is friendly to everyone but sometimes too rough - bumps into people, knocks over work by accident. He's not being mean, just has big movements. Working on body control.

Noah sometimes resists redirection. If I say "please choose different work" he'll argue. Testing boundaries. Normal 4-year-old behavior.

Mia mostly works alone. Not unfriendly but not social yet. She's young and still adjusting.

---

AREAS NEEDING WORK

**Material organization**: Some materials getting mixed up. Need to do weekly check and reorganize.

**Ground rules**: Some kids still running, talking loudly. Need consistent reminders.

**Work cycle length**: Only about half the kids can stay engaged for the full 2-hour work period. Others get distracted, wander. Will improve with time.

**Language**: Multiple kids don't speak much English. Communication is challenging. Using lots of gestures, simple words, modeling.

---

THINGS GOING WELL

**Routine establishing**: Kids know the basic flow of the morning.

**Material care**: Most kids handle materials carefully. No major breakages.

**Respect**: Kids generally respect each other's work. Not a lot of interrupting.

**Interest**: Kids want to work with the materials. Curiosity is there.

---

FOCUS AREAS - PRACTICAL LIFE & SENSORIAL

Since this is Visit 1, focus is on practical life and sensorial foundations.

Practical Life: Kids working with pouring, spooning, folding, sweeping, buttoning. These build concentration, coordination, independence. Everyone doing at least some practical life work daily.

Sensorial: Pink Tower, Brown Stair, Color Tablets being used regularly by kids showing readiness. These develop visual discrimination and prepare for math later.

Both areas are getting attention. Foundation is being built.

---

CONCERNS

**One concern**: Leo's high energy. He struggles to focus. Often up and moving around. Not disruptive but not deeply engaged either. May need to consult with parents about strategies.

**Another concern**: Sophia avoiding structured work. She goes to art every day. Art is fine but she needs exposure to Montessori materials too. Will address gently next week.

**Language barrier**: This is going to be ongoing. Many families don't speak English. Communication with parents is difficult. Need translator for parent conferences.

---

NEXT STEPS FOR CLASSROOM

Materials to add:
- More varied pouring activities (different sized containers)
- Additional practical life exercises (food prep, polishing)
- Sound cylinders (sensorial)

Lessons to prepare:
- Brown Stair for Oscar and Emma
- More color work for kids ready for Box 2
- Introduction to grace and courtesy lessons

Continue building:
- Concentration through repeated practice
- Independence through less teacher intervention
- Community through modeling respect and care

---

ASSESSMENT OF MONTH ONE

Overall: Solid start. Classroom community is forming. Kids are learning routines and beginning to work with materials. Foundation being established.

Challenges: Normal first-month challenges - kids learning boundaries, materials getting disorganized, energy levels varying, language barriers.

Strengths: Kids show interest in materials, environment is prepared, routine is establishing, most kids making progress toward independence.

This is a marathon not a sprint. We're building foundation now that will support all learning for rest of year.

